Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @pak choi{1} and thinly slice widthways. Trim and halve the @green beans{80%g}.

Zest and halve the @lime{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on high heat.
Once hot, add the @sliced mushrooms{120%g} to the pan and fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir the @red Thai style paste{75%g}, @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and garlic into the mushrooms.
Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.
Meanwhile, drain the @king prawns{150%g}.

Add the prawns, @coconut milk{200%ml}, @soy sauce{25%ml}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{200%ml} into the pan.
Bring to the boil, then add the green beans and the pak choi. Simmer until just tender, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw prawns. Cook so they're opaque in the middle.

Add the @udon noodles{220%g} to the soup and cook, using a #fork{} to gently separate them, until warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove the pan from the heat. Stir in the lime zest and half the lime juice.
Taste the soup and add more @salt{}, @pepper{}, lime juice and sugar if needed.

Share the udon noodle soup between your #bowls{}.
Cut any remaining lime into wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!